< Review>
This is the LGBT(Q) Building. They have so many services that they offer, most free of charge. There is the Jeffrey Goodman Special Care Clinic and Pharmacy, where you can receive medical care and medication prescribed to you. They pretty much have you covered if you're HIV positive but they are not limited to the poz community. They are also working towards preventive measures, such as Prep, etc. Very informative and helpful to all in need of their services.<//Review>

< review>
These guys are honest and the first place to take your car when you need body work.  I had two experiences with them and both were great- Highly recommended.
Someone smashed my right mirror while my car was parked on the street. Anaheim Hills Auto Body could have easily charged me  for a new mirror and new paint. But instead he found a used part for $ much less money.
Anaheim Hills Auto Body responded quickly by text and was a cool dude to work with. Paul is honest and professional. He is now my go-to guy for any auto work.</review>

<text>Repair shops and insurance are usually a pain to deal with.
This place honestly surprised me in a very good way.

My adjuster was being a pain since I could never reach her, so I was already not too happy with my car situation.
I brought my car into this shop due to its proximity to my home and was pleasantly treated throughout the whole process:
-My calls were always picked up pretty fast, I had no issues waiting or reaching voice mails. The receptionist, (didnt get her name) always took my messages or did her best effort to reach out the person handling my case asap, even if he was busy.
-Francisco J, was the person in charge of my car and was spectacular when doing his job. He explained every single thing he would do to my car and gave me realistic timelines as to how long it would take and which steps depended on other people.
The minute he found something else wrong with my car, he called and explained the extra parts, costs, and process that would be required.
In my particular case, he had to get approval for one extra part and I was really expecting the worst since my Adjuster was not reachable; however, Francisco got a quick hold of her and got the approval on a very timely manner.
-The car was delivered to me one day after the estimated completion, and that not a problem due to the transparent communication. It was very clean (just washed) and the pieces and paint job were done perfectly.
-Also, I needed a rental car and this shop manages to coordinate perfectly with the car rental so that you get picked up and even return the car in their premises. It really is an experience where you don't have to worry at all.

<review>I've always wanted to have a "real" premium steakhouse experience.  Other well-known establishments were premium in price, but not in quality. This place delivered.

We went here for my wife's birthday.  At the servers recommendation our table of 6 split a MASSIVE tomohawk.

Aged for 90 days,  cooked perfectly and well presented. The tomohawk did not disappoint.

With numerous sides, lots of corkage, and other impaired decisions dinner was about $100 pp which is about typical for other places like this.  For this locale and quality I felt this was excellent.

Ambiance and decor were outstanding.  We will be back.</review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNzyxzY_ofck9CvBEl5X3CDrrRiLPbHKR938i6s=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO_A66b6YUvqmHJW0bhNhpGKGcy9_55k1sukcBO=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< Response>

<Date>1576213705976</Date><rating>2</rating><review>Heard great things and as a Yountville resident I was excited to experience APL! Unfortunately the service needs a lot to work. Arrived at 6:24pm for a 6:30 reservation. Was told by the hostess that I was early and needed to wait in the lounge so I could “ be seated closer to my reservation time.... “ So we waited in the lounge until they were ready to seat us.
To start we ordered the radishes, “artisanal“ bread and crab cakes. They never served us the crab cakes, not sure why. Radishes were awesome. Bread was exactly the same pain d’epi you get at Bouchon Bakery...not what I was looking for and probably not a great idea to serve the same exact type of bread from
Bouchon Bakery! Half way through the appetizers the servers took our appetizers and plates away as we were still enjoying everything, not asking if we were done, just randomly taking everything away very quickly.  They provided us with large hot dinner plates immediately seeming as if our entrees were coming right out. However it was a good 20 min until our entrees arrived. Not sure what the rush was to remove our apps so quickly.  For dinner we all shared the short ribs, rib eye, escarole and fries. The steak knives they provided could barely cut the rib eye. The rib eye was very good, but the knives were extremely dull and provided a poor experience at a steak house. There was never any feedback from staff during our meal. The food was good but not exceptional. I’m sure the experience would be better if the service was better.
Was overly disappointed in the hostess telling us we had to wait to be seated closer to our reservation time when our table was set and ready. Mr. Lang - what time do you want your guests to arrive in order to be seated at a reserved table? It’s ok to ask us to wait until our table is ready, not tell us to wait until we are closer to our reservation time, arriving 6 minutes early. How much closer did we need to be to get seated?<//review>< pictures>
None<//pictures>

<name>Russ Martin</name>< Date>
1574186903469</Date>
< Rate>
3< /Rate>
<Text>After seeing a new steakhouse was opening in Yountville, my fiancé and I were excited to see how it measured up against some of the other world-famous steakhouses we've been lucky enough to have eaten at over the years. Unfortunately, Perry Lang's did not live up to any of them. Before we get there, let me say that the restaurant decor is stunning and Adam, the manager who was on the night we ate, is top notch. Adam was beyond kind, knowledgeable, and really is the only reason we gave this restaurant a third star. Our waiter seemed wildly overwhelmed, rarely paying attention to our table, and at the end of the night, actually verbalized to us "I'm sorry I haven't been at your table very often. We're quite busy." Typically, we wouldn't mind this but when you're sitting down to a $300 dinner and the restaurant is not actually all that big, and very well staffed, not being paid attention to by your waiter is tough. To this issue though, Adam the manager was really our main waiter so not too big of an issue, more so off-putting. We had a good salad, some fantastic bread that they bring in from Bouchon Bakery across the street, and finally it was time for the main course. My fiancé's filet was fantastic. Expertly cooked, fantastic flavors, a well-worth it at the price point. Unfortunately for my meal, my steak fell flat. I ordered the bone-in New York strip which is incredibly thin, had large deposits of fat throughout it, and cooked medium to medium-well, when I ordered it medium rare. For a nearly $60 steak, simply put it was embarrassing. When our waiter finally came back to our table after quite some time, he asked if I'd like to bring it home. At this point, I was finally able to let him know it was simply not what I ordered and he looked completely lost. Again, enter Adam who helped with the bill and made the meal justifiable for the price point. We felt for Adam as we watched another table display some serious issues with their meal as well, this table much more demonstrative and theatrical. The restaurant is new and I think can get better, but with the prices they charge, my advice is you are better off not risking it and heading to one of the other, more established options throughout the town.</Text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Resp>
None</Resp>

<user_name>Farzin P</user_name>< Text>
They took a week to change a flat tire. Other tire shops in the area would have been able to get the tire the next day, Since the car had already been on the truck once, I decided to just wait and let them fix it instead of towing it again.  I assumed the dealer would be the best equipped to take care of my car, but this was a mistake. I drive a current model(which does not come with a spare) and they don't stock any tires and take longer than anyone else to order. The service rep didn't seem to think this was unreasonable. If you have a tire issue, i would recommend going somewhere else.</Text>

<username>Antony Van Couvering</username>< UserId.>
115777027947436477370<//UserId.>
< review>
I got through the McClarens, Bentleys and turbocharged 911s and got out of this place for $0.00!

A tire place in Vegas lost the key for the locking lug nuts on my 911 (I had a flat in the desert and needed a new tire). Ever since then I’ve been dreading another flat in the desert, but this time without a hope of getting the donut wheel on.  These idiotic locking nuts had to go, and a search of YouTube convinced me I was not going to get them off with a cold chisel or a drill or anything else.

Porsche makes 20+ variations of their lock, so I had no choice but to enter into the hushed world of $300 branded polo shirts and keychains.  I dreaded it.

But guess what?  They were *super* nice.  Took care of me, got those albatrosses off my wheels and couldn’t have been more pleasant (or quick).

Thank you excellent staff!

As a bonus, I met for the first time, in the parking lots, the completely absurd Bentley Bentayga, surely up there with the Pacer in pantheon of automobile ugliness.  I took a photo and all my friends and I had a good laugh.<//review>

Drinks were average. Boba or agar was nothing new. Too much ice in the drinks, so maybe in winter, the server should ask would you like a normal amount of ice, which would be about 1/2 of the cup? At least give customer, especially a new one, a warning that 1/2 of the drink will be ice. To be fair, taiyakis were decent, except mine had some burnt fragments/crumbs embedded into some parts of it, which means the taiyaki machine/stove is not being cleaned well... Hopefully the workers/managers/owners will get their act together, and make this place a little better...< /Text>

< review>
Here is my new favorite boba hotspot! They have amazing boba and food items too like Turkey and Cheese and Nutella Croyakis, Jin Dui sesame balls, popcorn chicken.... mmm. You can also order and pay ahead on their app "Boba R Us". Super awesome right? I am still making my way through their menu, but my favorite boba drink so far is the Vintage milk tea with boba and crema. Soooo delicious and smooth. You can also adjust the sweetness to your liking. Def, checkout this place if you haven't already. Btw, the restaurant is clean and the staff is rocking. Love it!</review>

< Text>
A small but fully-equipped, fun, and exciting venue for local sports and entertainment. Seating is well distributed, so there are no bad views. A variety of counters serve just about any kind of event food you might want, while the on-site gift shop offers a huge selection of Storm merchandise. Parking is plentiful and reasonably priced.</Text>

<UserId.>112601884386842448959</UserId.><username>Thomas Griffiths< /username><Time>1528151577799<//Time><Rate>5</Rate><Review>A great place to take in a ballgame. Advice for a better experience...go early, buy a regular seat at least a week prior, (do not expect to be comfortable in the grass), expect to pay $5 for parking, $7 for the kid zone experience and expect to spend a lot on concessions, you'll have a much better time knowing these things.< /Review></record>

< user_id>
104989632032912842201< /user_id>
< Name>
Craig Shrand<//Name>
< Date>
1497464193925<//Date>
<rate>4</rate><Text>This is a minor league baseball park, home to Lake Elsinore Storm, affiliate of the San Diego Padres. Besides the game itself, entertainment always includes enjoyable skits mostly focusing on kids' participation. Venu is laid out well, partially because attendance is fairly sparse, depending on draw of team's opponents. Parking fee is pretty low and located close to the entrance of the park. And, there are special attractions almost every game like fireworks on many Fridays and flat-out free hot dogs on other days. As a senior riding a motorcycle to the games, there are double savings. Tickets for seats just feet away from home plate are an unbelievable$10. Once inside, PA system announces players' names and other information that doesn't interfere with actual play on the field.
